# The Ratchet: Open Source, Closed Source, and the Engine of Technological Progress

## An Essay on the Symbiotic Cycle Driving Computing, the Web, and Artificial Intelligence

-----

## Part I: Origins, Dominance, Erosion, and the AI Explosion

-----

### Prologue

Origin Pilot released as open source. Quantum is moving. And in the background, a pattern as old as computing itself is repeating — accelerated, amplified, and freighted with consequences that dwarf anything the Linux or WordPress eras produced. To understand where this is going, we have to look at where it’s been: open source’s early inception and rise through WordPress, the competition with closed source ebbing the market from open source, and how AI is now changing the entire landscape — from models to code to the evolution of open source itself. We must note the closed-source impact, the current closed-source model shifts like Mythos and Muse Spark, and what all of it means for the trajectory ahead. This is that story, told in full.

-----

### I. The Original Open Source Movement (1950s–2000s)

Software sharing began as the default — in the 1950s and 1960s, source code was distributed freely with hardware, and universities shared modifications openly following academic principles of knowledge sharing. This was the natural state of computing. Then, in the 1970s, companies realized software was more profitable than hardware, and proprietary licensing took hold.

Richard Stallman launched the GNU Project in 1983 and founded the Free Software Foundation in 1985, formalizing the moral and practical case for users’ rights to study, modify, and distribute software. He built almost everything needed for a complete free operating system — except the kernel.

In 1991, Linus Torvalds built the Linux kernel, fulfilling the missing piece of Stallman’s vision. Then came the LAMP stack era — Linux, Apache, MySQL, PHP — which became the backbone of the dotcom explosion. The term “open source” was formally adopted in 1998, when the Open Source Initiative was co-founded by Eric Raymond and Bruce Perens, deliberately rebranding “free software” into business-friendly language.

Systems based on a common “stack” of software with the Linux kernel at the base, Apache providing web services, the database engine MySQL to store data, and the programming language PHP to provide dynamic pages, came to be termed LAMP systems. In actuality, the programming language that predated PHP and dominated the web in the mid and late 1990s was Perl. Web forms were processed on the server side through Common Gateway Interface scripts written in Perl. The term “open source,” as related to free software, was in common use by 1995. In 1997, Eric S. Raymond published “The Cathedral and the Bazaar,” a reflective analysis of the hacker community and free software principles. The paper received significant attention in early 1998 and was one factor in motivating Netscape Communications Corporation to release their popular Netscape Communicator Internet suite as free software.

The Apache Software Foundation was established in 1999. The first members were some of the creators of the Apache HTTP server, which was released in 1995. In 1999, Sourceforge.com was launched, allowing developers to easily share and develop source code. In 2000, the Linux Foundation was founded. In 2005, Linus Torvalds created the initial version of Git, an open-source version control system to speed up the distributed development of the Linux kernel. In 2008, GitHub.com was launched — a central platform for source code development based on Git. Also in 2008, Google released the first version of Android, today’s most used mobile operating system.

The late 1990s and early 2000s marked the professionalization of open source with the IPOs of companies like Red Hat and VA Linux, which commercialized Linux distributions. Mozilla Firefox’s release in 2004 further expanded open source’s reach into web browsing, emphasizing privacy and security. These developments showcased open source’s economic potential and its ability to support sustainable business models.

The history of free and open-source software begins at the advent of computer software in the early half of the 20th century. In the 1950s and 1960s, computer operating software and compilers were delivered as a part of hardware purchases without separate fees. At the time, source code — the human-readable form of software — was generally distributed with the software, providing the ability to fix bugs or add new functions. Universities were early adopters of computing technology. Many of the modifications developed by universities were openly shared, in keeping with the academic principles of sharing knowledge, and organizations sprung up to facilitate sharing. As large-scale operating systems matured, fewer organizations allowed modifications to the operating software, and eventually such operating systems were closed to modification.

The roots of open-source software go deep, wide, and far back into the past, as early as the 1950s. In 1953, the A-2 system (an equivalent of today’s compilers) was released together with its source code, and customers were asked to send any improvements to UNIVAC (the Universal Automatic Computer). There were a few decades of open-source “silence” after the 1950s. The late 1970s and early 1980s saw a shift toward proprietary software as legal decisions granted software copyright protection, enabling commercial licensing models. In response, Stallman launched the GNU Project — and the cycle began.

