### II. WordPress and Open Source’s Peak Dominance

WordPress launched in 2003 as a simple blogging tool. What happened next is one of the most extraordinary market captures in software history. As of 2026, WordPress powers 43.5% of all websites and 62.8% of the CMS market. Despite the rise of modern frameworks and no-code builders, WordPress has actually increased its overall web share by 1.2 percentage points year-over-year. Its dominance is structural: the ecosystem of developers, plugins, themes, and hosting providers creates switching costs that no competitor has overcome at scale.

From 2011 to 2026, WordPress usage grew from 13.1% to 43.1% of all websites — roughly 810 million sites. WordPress commands a 64.2% market share among all CMS platforms. Each day, over 500 new WordPress sites are launched. This is more than just the CMS market share. When you take out the sites that don’t run on any known CMS, WordPress holds nearly two-thirds of the entire market. The next highest competitor is not close; Shopify has about 6.2% of the market.

WordPress *is* the open source success story at consumer scale. It proved that community-driven, free, infinitely-extensible software could utterly dominate an industry.

Security remains the platform’s most significant liability: WordPress sites face approximately 90,000 attacks per minute, and 97% of WordPress security vulnerabilities originate in plugins and themes rather than core software. Organizations running WordPress need dedicated security infrastructure — the default installation is not enterprise-grade without additional hardening.

WooCommerce controls 36% of all online stores globally and processed an estimated $35 billion in gross merchandise volume in 2025, making it the largest open-source eCommerce platform by transaction volume.

The bifurcation trend tells its own story: WordPress is simultaneously growing in total market share and declining in developer preference for new projects. The install base continues to expand through non-developer users while developer-led projects increasingly choose React-based frameworks, headless CMS solutions, or visual builders. WordPress remains excellent for content-heavy sites with non-technical editors, adequate for eCommerce through WooCommerce, and increasingly outmatched for performance-critical or developer-experience-driven projects.

Among the top 5,000 domains — the high-traffic, enterprise segment — open source still leads. Open source technology (WordPress plus Drupal) claims the majority share (over 51.7%) even among the world’s largest sites, dispelling the myth that open source is only for small businesses. WordPress has seen a greater percentage increase in enterprise adoption over time than any other CMS and is on track to become the first choice for enterprise organizations. For many years, the notion that “something without a license couldn’t be good” prevailed when it came to large-scale global web projects, and proprietary solutions such as Adobe Experience Manager and Sitecore were commonly considered “safe” bets. But times have changed, drastically, and as new technologies and younger audiences have ushered in the need to go to market even faster — a place where open source technologies shine — usage of WordPress in the enterprise has increased.

-----

### III. Closed Source Fights Back: The SaaS Erosion

But here’s where the pattern reveals its counter-rhythm. WordPress peaked at 65.2% CMS market share in 2022 and has since declined to 60.2%. What ate into it? Closed, proprietary SaaS platforms.

Shopify grew from 0.3% market share in 2014 to 7.0% in 2025 — a 23x increase. Meanwhile, Joomla dropped from 9.3% to 1.9%, and Drupal from 5.5% to 1.1%. The pattern: open source CMS competitors didn’t lose to WordPress; they lost to *closed* platforms. In U.S. ecommerce specifically, SaaS platforms — Shopify, Squarespace, and Wix — collectively command 67.2% of the market, while open-source platforms like WooCommerce and Ecwid account for about 21.7%.

The closed-source pitch was seductive: no server management, no plugin security nightmares, no maintenance. The non-technical user increasingly chose convenience. SaaS ecommerce platforms are decidedly more popular, and while open-source platforms offer customization and flexibility, they carry challenges that SaaS solutions help avoid. With a SaaS tool, you get a steady stream of product updates and new features. Open-source platforms, on the other hand, come with ongoing responsibilities that can catch entrepreneurs off guard — all software updates, bug fixes, and technical troubleshooting require continuous attention and specialized expertise.

The trade-off between proprietary convenience and open-source freedom plays out in a specific tension: if you use a proprietary ecommerce platform like Shopify or Wix, you’re beholden to the terms of their licenses, which are much more stringent. Shopify has suspended stores selling CBD products, supplements, and even vintage items that triggered fraud filters — sometimes with little warning and limited appeal options. You could suddenly lose all the hard work you’ve put into your online store. In contrast, when you choose an open source tool like WooCommerce, you can use it for anything you’d like.

Shopify has a 36% better total cost of ownership than WooCommerce according to its own data — though this claim warrants scrutiny given the source. In a 2024 survey by Perforce, 44.29% of respondents cited a lack of professional support and maintenance as a barrier to open-source adoption. This is the eternal vulnerability of open source: freedom requires capability.

The headless CMS market — neither fully open nor fully closed, but an architectural hybrid — was valued at $0.86 billion in 2024 and is projected to reach $4.59 billion by 2033. This represents the emerging middle ground: open-source backends with proprietary front-end delivery layers.

