### IV. AI Blows the Doors Open Again

Then AI happened, and the entire open-source/closed-source dynamic got reorganized. Here are the major open source AI developments that constitute a genuine paradigm shift.

**The Open Source AI Timeline:**

**2023:** Meta (Facebook) emerged as a major player in open-source AI by releasing the LLaMA series of large language models, cracking open frontier-scale models for the first time.

**2024:** Meta’s Llama 3 family expanded the frontier. Mistral released multiple competitive open models. Alibaba’s Qwen series emerged as a force. Mistral integrated a vision component: in November 2024, Pixtral Large combined a 1B-parameter vision encoder with the text model for multimodal image understanding. DeepSeek unveiled DeepSeek-R1-Lite-Preview in November, incorporating reasoning capabilities. In December, DeepSeek-V3 was released.

**January 2025:** DeepSeek launched its R1 model, providing responses comparable to GPT-4 and o1 at a fraction of the cost. The company claims it trained its V3 model for $6 million — far less than the $100 million cost for OpenAI’s GPT-4 in 2023 — and using approximately one-tenth the computing power consumed by Meta’s comparable model, Llama 3.1. DeepSeek significantly reduced training expenses by incorporating techniques such as mixture of experts (MoE) layers, training during ongoing trade restrictions on AI chip exports to China, using weaker AI chips intended for export and employing fewer units overall. Observers said this breakthrough sent “shock waves” through the industry, described as triggering a “Sputnik moment” for the US.

DeepSeek overtook ChatGPT as the most downloaded free app on the Apple App Store in the US. Many believe its rapid rise could be a significant step in democratizing AI, allowing smaller companies, start-ups and individual developers to build on DeepSeek-R1. DeepSeek’s models are described as “open-weight,” meaning the exact parameters are openly shared, but the training data is not openly licensed. Since the January 2025 debut, the company has made its new models available under free and open-source software licenses, primarily the MIT License.

Marc Andreessen hailed DeepSeek as “one of the most amazing and impressive breakthroughs I’ve ever seen — and as open source, a profound gift to the world.” AI scholar Kai-Fu Lee declared that “the biggest revelation from DeepSeek is that open-source has won.”

The full-sized 671-billion-parameter model, as well as its smaller distilled versions, were made available through public repositories such as Hugging Face. This openness invited collaboration from researchers around the world and created an alternative to the increasingly closed ecosystems of models like OpenAI’s GPT-4 or Anthropic’s Claude series. For the broader AI community, R1 symbolized the return of accessibility and transparency to frontier-level research — qualities that had been fading from the industry’s top tiers.

The launch had far-reaching effects globally. On the stock market, U.S. tech stocks for AI companies took a significant hit, caused by panic selloffs stemming from concerns over the potential disruption of the top positions of companies such as Nvidia and OpenAI.

**Mid-2025:** Alibaba open-sources Qwen3 variants. Moonshot AI debuted Kimi K2, praised for its open-research focus. Zhipu open-sourced GLM-4.5, a 130B-parameter model tailored for intelligent-agent applications. Mistral’s lineup included “Mistral Small 3.1” (24B, Apache-2.0) and specialized models like Devstral, an open-source 24B code assistant released under Apache 2.0, optimized to run on a single NVIDIA RTX 4090 or even a 32GB RAM Mac. Devstral reportedly outperforms leading open models like Google’s Gemma 3 27B on the SWE-Bench code benchmark. This specialization strategy — creating domain-specific models — shows the power of open development to target niche needs.

By mid-2024, there was a clear trend toward open-source LLMs in enterprise. Enterprises found that they could fine-tune open models on their proprietary data to achieve better accuracy on domain-specific tasks than a one-size-fits-all model. Developers were running LLMs locally on personal devices — something unheard of with GPT-3-sized models a few years ago. A moderately powerful PC with an RTX 4090 GPU could host a 13B or even 30B parameter model efficiently, thanks to techniques like 4-bit quantization.

**Late 2025:** DeepSeek released V3.1 under MIT License, featuring a hybrid architecture with thinking and non-thinking modes, surpassing prior models by over 40% on certain benchmarks. V3.2 followed in December 2025. The Agentic AI Foundation formed under the Linux Foundation in December 2025, anchored by contributions from Anthropic’s Model Context Protocol (MCP), OpenAI’s AGENTS.md, and Block’s goose framework. When competing labs contribute infrastructure to a neutral body, something structural is happening.

China’s open-source embrace upended conventional wisdom. DeepSeek’s success proved that open-source strategies can lead to faster innovation and broad adoption. Zhipu AI announced that 2025 would be “the year of open source.” Baidu released Ernie 4.5 and Ernie X1, making them free for individual users and planning open-source release. Companies were compelled to make these moves following DeepSeek’s emergence — with DeepSeek free, it became impossible for any other Chinese competitor to charge for the same thing.

**February 2026:** China released Origin Pilot, its first domestically developed quantum operating system, for public download. The operating system, called Origin Pilot, was made available online, developed by Hefei-based Origin Quantum Computing Technology Co. Origin Pilot was first launched in 2021 and has undergone multiple rounds of iteration and upgrades. It is currently deployed on the Origin Wukong series of quantum computers.

The broader context is China’s push into what policymakers describe as “industries of the future.” Quantum technology is among six strategic sectors highlighted in recommendations for the country’s 15th Five-Year Plan covering 2026 to 2030. The list also includes biomanufacturing, hydrogen and nuclear fusion power, brain-computer interfaces, embodied artificial intelligence, and 6G communications.

Guo Guoping, chief scientist of Origin Quantum, called a quantum operating system the “soft heart” of the quantum computing ecosystem. Making Origin Pilot available globally marks a shift from “closed-door tech innovation” toward open-source ecosystem development. The system supports multiple hardware platforms and manages core functions such as task scheduling, hardware-software coordination, parallel execution, and automatic qubit calibration.

The decision to open-source the “soft heart” of China’s quantum stack is a calculated move. By allowing global download, China seeks to establish a de facto standard in quantum software and attract international developers. The underlying OriginQ Wukong hardware, featuring 72 functional qubits and 126 coupler qubits, has already executed over 339,000 quantum jobs for users in 120-plus countries, with American researchers reportedly among the most active users.

Origin Pilot is released in two versions: a Community Edition for free download (focusing on noise mitigation and hybrid compilation) and an Enterprise Edition which includes advanced post-quantum cryptography tools. Neither IBM, Google, nor any other Western quantum company offers their underlying quantum operating system as a downloadable package for local installation. IBM’s Qiskit and Google’s Cirq are primarily accessed via the cloud.

The choice is obvious — not because Origin Pilot is necessarily superior, but because it’s available. And in technology ecosystem dynamics, availability compounds. Every institution that adopts Origin Pilot becomes a node in China’s quantum software ecosystem, generating feedback, bug reports, driver contributions, and, critically, a community of developers fluent in Origin Quantum’s abstractions and architectural assumptions.

This playbook should look familiar. When DeepSeek released its R1 reasoning model as open source in January 2025, the immediate reaction focused on performance benchmarks versus Western competitors. The strategic consequence was different: it catalyzed an ecosystem. Within a year, Chinese open-source AI models had gone from under 2% to nearly 30% of global AI usage. Alibaba’s Qwen models overtook Meta’s Llama in cumulative downloads on Hugging Face.

**March 2026:** The AI landscape moved beyond the “chatbot” era into the “agentic” era. OpenClaw surpassed React to become the most-starred software project in GitHub history, boasting over 335,000 stars. The surge reflected a fundamental shift in developer preference toward local-first, persistent AI agents that run on a user’s own hardware under their own rules.

In direct competition with Western models, Zhipu AI launched GLM-5.1 on March 27, 2026, achieving 94.6% of the score recorded by Anthropic’s Claude Opus 4.6 on coding benchmarks. The architecture involves a 744 billion parameter Mixture-of-Experts system leveraging 40 billion active parameters per token. The broader implication: the model was trained entirely on a self-sufficient Chinese compute stack using Huawei Ascend 910B chips, demonstrating that top-tier AI results are now achievable without access to restricted Western hardware. This signals a decoupling of the global AI supply chain.

MCP crossed 97 million installs in March 2026, cementing its transition from experimental standard to foundational agentic infrastructure. Every major AI provider now ships MCP-compatible tooling.

**April 2026:** DeepSeek released a preview of its V4 model, continuing its open-source approach. The release came more than a year after R1 rocked global tech markets. Similar to DeepSeek’s previous releases, V4 is open-source, allowing developers to download the code, run it locally, and modify it. Huawei confirmed that its latest AI computing cluster, powered by Ascend AI processors, can support DeepSeek’s V4 model.

Stanford’s 2026 AI Index tracked 87 notable model releases from industry in 2025, compared to just seven from all other sources. Models released by industry now make up over 90 percent of notable models, up from just under 50 percent in 2015, and zero in 2003. AI-related GitHub projects rocketed to 5.58 million through 2025 — a roughly fivefold increase since 2020 and a 23.7 percent increase from 2024.

AI investment set a new record with over $581 billion spent in 2025 — more than double the $253 billion spent in 2024.

